Vheadline
p2
VFest ends on a high note
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe fourth evening of the six-day festival of music, dance and drama of Visakha Music and Dance Academy at its auditorium Kalabharathi witnessed an engrossing violin solo.Former principal of M.R. Govt. College of Music and Dance, Vizianagaram, Dwaram Durgaprasada Rao, ably supported on another violin by his younger brother Satyanarayana (AIR staffer, Hyderabad) rendered it evolving an exquisite blend of nuances of exposition of carnatic music and the intrinsic qualities of violin.Expansive expatiation ofMarakathavalli(Kambhoji) and RTP in Raagamalika with the lyrics coined with their names;Sankarabharanam, Todi, Kalyani and Darbar were the highlights. Emanating pure and elatedlayabhavamboth in his following andThani, veteran mridangam player V. Kamalakararao from Rajahmundry contributed splendour.The next evening, Dr. Nityasri Mahadevan in the company of M.A. Krishnaswamy on violin, Sivakumar on mridangam (both from Chennai) and G. Venkatarao on ghatam, rendered a scintillating vocal recital.RTP in Raagamalika comprised Mohana, Sama, Brindavani and Saranga, which also appeared knit as lyrics were the highlights.Rendering ofSwaraprastaramin the reverse order and its extension into about a score of ragas was a special attraction. The festival concluded on an absorbing note with the staging of the last few episodes of the poetic playSatyaharischandraof late Balijepalli Lakshmikantham on Thursday evening.Surabhi Jamunarani from Hyderabad living the role of Chandramukhi presented a memorable picture of an embodiment of an aesthetic blend of soulful appeal of all the four facets of acting viz., Aangikam, Vachikam, Mukhacham and Satwikam (empathy).Gummadi Gopalakrishna as the emperor, Dr. Meegada Ramalingaswamy who directed the play as Nakshatraka and B.A. Naidu as Kaalakoushika and Veerabahu, did well sustaining the tempo.
